This question checks whether you accept feedback professionally and improve from it. The best answers usually come from code review or design feedback, since that’s common for developers.

Use the STAR structure:

Situation

Feedback

Action

Result

Example Answer (Very Good for Developers)

In one of my previous projects, I implemented a feature that involved fetching related data from multiple tables. During the code review, a senior developer pointed out that my implementation could lead to an N+1 query problem, which could affect performance when the dataset grows.

Initially, I wasn’t fully aware of the performance impact, so he explained how eager loading could improve the query efficiency. I refactored the code using the appropriate Rails methods to avoid multiple database calls.

That feedback helped me understand the importance of analyzing database queries more carefully. Since then, I’ve been more mindful about query optimization and performance when designing backend logic.

Another Example (Team Collaboration)

In a previous project, during a code review my lead suggested that my method was doing too many responsibilities and recommended splitting the logic into smaller service methods.

I took that feedback positively and refactored the code to follow a cleaner structure. It improved readability and made the code easier to maintain. Since then, I try to design code with better separation of responsibilities from the beginning.

Why This Works

This answer shows:

✅ You accept feedback
✅ You improve technically
✅ You collaborate well with the team

What NOT to Say ❌

Avoid answers like:

“I usually don’t receive critical feedback.”

“My manager was wrong.”

“I argued with the reviewer.”

That gives a negative impression.

💡 Small trick:
After answering, you can add one line:

I actually appreciate constructive feedback because it helps improve both the code quality and my own learning.

Managers like this mindset.

